<DOC><DOCNO> AP891109-0257 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0049EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     11-09 0860</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0900</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Senate has given final passage tolegislation to raise the hourly minimum wage to $4.25 by April1991, the first increase in the floor wage since 1981. PresidentBush is expected to sign the bill next week.   The 89-8 Senate vote Wednesday came eight days after Bush andcongressional Democrats agreed on the plan to boost the minimumwage by 45 cents next April 1 and another 45 cents a year later.   The measure, passed overwhelmingly by the House last week, alsocreates a new, subminimum wage that could be paid to teen-agers fortheir first three months in the work force and up to three monthsmore for those in certified training or education programs.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Treasury has begun replenishing itscoffers after last-minute congressional action raising the debtlimit averted the government's first-ever default.   The Treasury on Wednesday sold $16 billion in three- andsix-month bills in its weekly auction that was postponed on Mondaybecause the government's borrowing authority had dropped to $2.8trillion, a level its debt already surpassed.   The drop also forced postponement of $40 billion in quarterlyrefunding auctions and Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady saidthe government would default if Congress had failed to act bymidnight Tuesday, which it didn't.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Representatives of the Machinists union andCondor Partners have met amid reports the UAL Corp. board ofdirectors has given its chairman permission to explore thepossibility of a buyout or recapitalization of United Airlines'parent.   The meeting in Washington, D.C., was held Wednesday to hear whatCondor is planning for UAL, a union spokesman said.   He said the union was not seeking to reach any immediateagreements with Condor, which was formed by Coniston Partners, aNew York investment group that announced last week it hadaccumulated a 9.7 percent stake in Chicago-based UAL.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. Sentencing Commission has unveileddraft guidelines for punishing corporate wrongdoers that woulddramatically increase fines for companies convicted of federalcrimes.   The draft guidelines, published Wednesday in the FederalRegister, contain elaborate formulas for calculating the fines thatcompanies would be required to pay for a variety of federal crimes.   In recent years large frauds committed by big corporations haveincreased the average fine paid by companies from $48,000 between1984 and 1987 to $195,000 last year, according to a studiesperformed by the commission.</TEXT><DATELINE>CARROLL, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. net farm income will decline steadilythrough 1996 from its current record heights, researchers say.   The projections made Wednesday include forecasts of fallinggovernment subsidies, declining soybean prices and generally stableprices for cattle, hogs and corn.   The Food and Agricultural Policy Research Institute predicted a27 percent drop in net farm income by 1996, but said that stillwould leave the income figure higher than in any year before 1986.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The media concern Whittle Communications says itis developing a closed-circuit, advertiser-supported televisionnetwork for installation in 100,000 medical waiting roomsnationwide.   The company disclosed Wednesday that it was developing the newTV project on the same day that it launched the first in a seriesof non-fiction books that contain advertising and are being givenfor free to 150,000 civic and business leaders.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   RJR Nabisco Inc. has announced an agreement tosell its Nabisco food businesses in Spain and Portugal to a Spanishconcern for $77.5 million cash.   The deal announced Wednesday will bring RJR Nabisco close to itsgoal of divestng $5.5 billion in assets to raise cash and reducedebt amassed in its $24.53 billion leveraged buyout by KohlbergKravis Roberts andamp; Co., spokesman David Kalis said.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Federal Express Co. commercial that featuredan incredibly fast-speaking businessman was the best advertisementof the 1980s, according to a survey of the board of the ad tradegroup, The One Club.   The Orwellian ``1984'' commercial for Apple Computer Inc. and aseries of Rolling Stone magazine print ads noting the differencesbetween some perceptions about its readers and reality also wereranked among the best ads of the decade, the group said Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   PacifiCorp has announced a $1.7 billion buyoutoffer for Arizona Public Service Co., the state's biggest utilityand the principal holding of troubled Pinnacle West Capital Corp.   Pinnacle West shares jumped sharply higher on the newsWednesday, finishing up $1.75 to $9.75 a share on the New YorkStock Exchange. Shares of Portland, Ore.-based PacifiCorp, autility holding company, finished down 50 cents at $41.87{.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market ran up a broad gain Wednesday, extendingTuesday's rally on signs of a new move toward a more stimulativeFederal Reserve credit policy. The Dow Jones industrial average, up14.96 on Tuesday, climbed 26.23 points to 2,623.36.   The dollar rose modestly against most major currencies.   Treasury bill prices rose while longer-term securities weremixed.   Energy futures prices slid; grain and soybeans and preciousmetals were mixed; copper declined slightly; and livestock and porkfutures mostly higher.</TEXT></DOC>